TankPilot Phase 4A – OBD-II Integration Foundation

Role

You are a senior Kotlin Multiplatform, Android, iOS, Bluetooth LE, and automotive software engineer.

Your task is to add a hardware abstraction layer that allows TankPilot to communicate with Bluetooth OBD-II adapters while keeping the application completely functional without one.

Goals

Create a provider-based telemetry architecture.

TankPilot must continue functioning normally without hardware.

When an adapter is connected, the app automatically upgrades to live vehicle telemetry.

Supported Adapters

Design for ELM327-compatible adapters.

Initially test against:

* OBDLink MX+
* OBDLink CX
* vLinker iCar2 BLE
* vLinker MC+
* VeePeak BLE

Do not hardcode support for any specific brand.

Architecture

Create:

VehicleTelemetryProvider

BluetoothObdTelemetryProvider

ManualTelemetryProvider

MockTelemetryProvider

FutureCloudTelemetryProvider

Every provider must expose identical interfaces.

Use Kotlin Flow for live updates.

Telemetry

Support live observation of:

* Vehicle Speed
* Engine RPM
* Engine Load
* Coolant Temperature
* Intake Air Temperature
* Battery Voltage
* VIN
* Engine Runtime
* Diagnostic Trouble Codes
* Check Engine Status
* Fuel Trim
* Mass Air Flow (when available)

If a vehicle does not support a PID, return Unknown instead of failing.

User Experience

When an adapter is connected:

Display:

“TankPilot Connect Active”

Show connection strength.

Show adapter model.

Allow disconnect/reconnect.

If disconnected while driving:

Continue estimating fuel using GPS until telemetry reconnects.

Never interrupt trip tracking.

Requirements

* Offline-first
* Dependency Injection
* Unit tested
* No brand-specific logic in shared code
* Automatic adapter discovery
* Clean architecture
* Production-ready implementation
